Maung lacks the two [[flap consonant|flapped]] [[lateral consonant|laterals]],<ref name="e118">Evans (1998): p. 118.</ref> which are quite unusual among Australian languages. Also unusual is the [[velar consonant|velar]] [[approximant consonant|approximant]] {{IPA|/ɰ/}}, which is an areal feature shared with [[Tiwi language|Tiwi]] and [[Kunbarlang language|Kunbarlang]].<ref>Evans (1998): p. 117.</ref>

==Relationships with other languages==
The vocabularies of all the Iwaidjan languages contain [[loanword]]s from [[Macassarese language|Macassarese]] and [[Malay language|Malay]],<ref name="e116">Evans (1998): p. 116.</ref> both [[Malayo-Polynesian languages]] from [[Indonesia]]. Iwaidja and Maung have also borrowed heavily from [[Kunwinjku language|Kunwijku]],<ref name="e116"/> another Australian language of the [[Gunwingguan languages|Gunwingguan]] family.

While the Iwaidjan languages share a number of features with other non-Pama–Nyungan language families, it is uncertain which they are closest related to.{{Citation needed|date=April 2007}} Ross has proposed that they form part of an [[Arnhem Land languages|Arnhem Land family]].

